&lt;p&gt;My Twitter feed typically spans from &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/sehurlburt/status/1042557375171899392&quot;&gt;soft skills&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://mobile.twitter.com/levelsio/status/956176482958639105&quot;&gt;startup culture&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/feministy/status/986427827481464833&quot;&gt;remote work&lt;/a&gt;, to &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/Nick_Craver/status/1046841014433005570&quot;&gt;developer fury&lt;/a&gt;, but I instantly reacted when I saw this tweet:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot; data-lang=&quot;en&quot;&gt;&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;üå∂ Hot take: Using the to-do app as the Hello World was a big step back for teaching devs.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;When the Twitter app was the Hello World, it taught everyone auth, associations, async requests, 3rd party APIs, offline, etc.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;mdash; Jonnie Hallman (@destroytoday) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/destroytoday/status/1024321627612426241?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&quot;&gt;July 31, 2018&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;YES. ABSOLUTELY YES.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Why does it feel like new app tutorials aren‚Äôt actually teaching me anything?  Where do I squeeze in professional development with earning my keep, pursuing healthy hobbies, and being present with family?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Enter Gatsby.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;What is Gatsby?&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
  &lt;a
